Rym: Just throw them in there in some sort of, like, RAID 10, 'cause whatever, and then just have that sit with your Fios constantly scheduled archive backups of everything.

862
00:44:22,154 --> 00:44:22,345
Rym: Mm-hmm.

863
00:44:22,732 --> 00:44:23,463
Rym: And just let it run.

864
00:44:23,524 --> 00:44:23,890
Rym: Let it hum.

865
00:44:24,451 --> 00:44:26,730
Scott: There are other things you might not think about backing up.

866
00:44:27,031 --> 00:44:30,748
Scott: The real hard problem is not something going down and surprising you.

867
00:44:31,430 --> 00:44:34,710
Scott: It's something you didn't realize that you wanted to back up, right?

868
00:44:35,410 --> 00:44:37,690
Scott: Like, data that you have you didn't really think about.

869
00:44:37,750 --> 00:44:42,309
Rym: Like, if you use Spotify or Netflix, and you, like -- you like musics.

870
00:44:42,590 --> 00:44:44,569
Rym: Like, you star some music, you make some playlists.

871
00:44:44,735 --> 00:44:44,930
Rym: Yup.

872
00:44:45,932 --> 00:44:51,430
Rym: You've raided, like, 4,000 movies in Netflix, 'cause I learned something disturbing, actually, yesterday.

873
00:44:51,673 --> 00:44:51,802
Rym: Mm-hmm.

874
00:44:52,110 --> 00:45:06,908
Rym: Apparently -- and I haven't verified this myself -- if you cancel the DVD part of Netflix, you can't see DVD-only movies in the interfaces anymore, and all your reviews of them and your star ratings are no longer accessible, and they'll never be recommended to you.

875
00:45:07,230 --> 00:45:08,984
Scott: What if you pay again?

876
00:45:09,065 --> 00:45:09,650
Scott: Will it come back?

877
00:45:09,792 --> 00:45:10,428
Rym: I don't know.

878
00:45:11,132 --> 00:45:12,870
Rym: I got to do some investigative journalism on that front.

879
00:45:12,870 --> 00:45:13,899
Scott: Why cancel Netflix altogether?

880
00:45:14,081 --> 00:45:15,050
Scott: So I lost everything.

881
00:45:15,070 --> 00:45:16,446
Rym: Yeah, I've thought about canceling it.

882
00:45:17,810 --> 00:45:18,889
Scott: But, yeah, stuff like that.

883
00:45:19,352 --> 00:45:26,669
Scott: Or another good example would be, like, not your Gmail, which is obvious, but, like, your Google Chat history, all your hangouts, every hangout you've ever done.

884
00:45:26,811 --> 00:45:28,029
Rym: Well, that's just in my history.

885
00:45:28,793 --> 00:45:29,909
Rym: It's right there in my email.

886
00:45:31,290 --> 00:45:32,057
Rym: It's in the same interface.

887
00:45:32,077 --> 00:45:33,450
Rym: It's in the same web screen.

888
00:45:33,530 --> 00:45:34,257
Scott: But it used to be.

889
00:45:34,278 --> 00:45:35,490
Scott: It used to not be, right?

890
00:45:35,751 --> 00:45:37,710
Scott: And maybe you've got, like, an IRC channel.

891
00:45:37,851 --> 00:45:39,429
Scott: You got a bot, like, backing that shit up.

892
00:45:39,975 --> 00:45:40,550
Scott: Well, you know what, kids?

893
00:45:40,550 --> 00:45:41,610
Scott: Everything anyone's ever chatted.

894
00:45:41,830 --> 00:45:53,170
Rym: As I said in the backups episode, I have an archive of every online digital conversation of text, typing, I have ever had since 1996.

895
00:45:53,170 --> 00:45:53,330
Rym: Mm-hmm.

896
00:45:53,592 --> 00:45:56,410
Rym: Everyone, every IM, every email.

897
00:45:57,110 --> 00:45:58,710
Rym: So take that, people.

898
00:46:00,174 --> 00:46:02,668
Rym: The first thing I ever said to Scott was, "Hey, I'm that long-haired guy.

899
00:46:03,030 --> 00:46:06,004
Rym: You want to meet at Gracie's for dinner at 6 before we go to the D&D

900
00:46:06,024 --> 00:46:06,247
Rym: thing?".

901
00:46:07,115 --> 00:46:08,830
Rym: That was the first message I ever sent to Scott.

902
00:46:09,534 --> 00:46:10,829
Rym: I looked it up ahead of time at this show.

903
00:46:12,692 --> 00:46:18,690
Scott: What kind of other things do I use where I'm storing my information on someone else's computer?

904
00:46:19,012 --> 00:46:25,187
Rym: It's mostly the throwaway comments, like, "I review something on a site, and I've reviewed enough things to where.

905
00:46:25,228 --> 00:46:27,127
Rym: now I have the sort of history of recommendations and

906
00:46:27,147 --> 00:46:27,430
Rym: reviews.".

907
00:46:27,490 --> 00:46:30,130
Rym: Like, the list of restaurants I order food from on Grubhub.

908
00:46:30,230 --> 00:46:37,650
Rym: If Grubhub disappeared, I would not remember the names of most of the restaurants that I order food from online that I've never visited in person.

909
00:46:38,211 --> 00:46:39,750
Rym: I don't even know where they are.

910
00:46:40,052 --> 00:46:41,730
Scott: There are some other things that might be kind of tricky.

911
00:46:41,910 --> 00:46:43,429
Scott: For example, Steam, right?

912
00:46:44,711 --> 00:46:53,270
Scott: On Steam, you should go to every Steam game in your list, and I don't know if you should necessarily, like, install every Steam game just in case Steam goes away, right?

913
00:46:53,430 --> 00:46:56,822
Scott: But maybe go through and get all the keys, 'cause you can do that.

914
00:46:56,843 --> 00:46:59,449
Scott: You can say, "Show me the CD keys from this game," right?

915
00:47:00,071 --> 00:47:02,690
Scott: And get them all into, like, a text file somewhere.

916
00:47:03,111 --> 00:47:17,009
Scott: That way, you know, if the game -- if Steam disappears, you can go find the installer for that game, install it legitimately and not, you know, piratey and spyware -- malwarey, and just paste your CD key in, and the game will work, right, even when Steam is gone.

917
00:47:17,575 --> 00:47:19,250
Scott: You'll still be able to get the installer from somewhere.

918
00:47:19,530 --> 00:47:32,010
Rym: Yeah, it's hard to say, 'cause at the same time, if Steam went down, it would piss off the kinds of people who would make sure that every one of those games was immediately available on some sort of pirated fashion.

919
00:47:32,150 --> 00:47:42,130
Scott: I mean, but in fact, if you're really paranoid about something like that, you know, your option is basically get a giant hard drive and install every Steam game you have all at once.

920
00:47:42,976 --> 00:47:45,530
Scott: Unlike me, where I only install the ones I'm sort of playing recently.

921
00:47:45,631 --> 00:47:52,170
Rym: If you're extra paranoid, then put the computer you downloaded them into into offline mode and then hibernate it.

922
00:47:52,170 --> 00:47:56,049
Scott: But any time you buy a new game, you got to turn it on, download the game, and hibernate it again.

923
00:47:56,491 --> 00:48:03,328
Rym: And then you keep VMs, images, of those hibernated states, so you can theoretically play those games forever no matter what.

924
00:48:05,173 --> 00:48:06,550
Rym: That's not a bad idea, actually.

925
00:48:06,852 --> 00:48:07,430
Scott: It's a lot of effort.

926
00:48:07,450 --> 00:48:08,229
Rym: I'm not gonna do it.

927
00:48:08,611 --> 00:48:10,910
Rym: If Steam goes down, I'm just gonna rabble about it.

928
00:48:11,090 --> 00:48:17,490
Scott: Yeah, it's really annoying, you know, some of these things don't have, like, a backup, you know, a way to do something about it.

929
00:48:18,090 --> 00:48:30,469
Rym: The real future is that normal people don't know or care, whatever, but if you're nerdy and you're smart, try to only rely upon services that give you an API and/or are federated.

930
00:48:31,413 --> 00:48:36,828
Rym: If a service is not one or both of those things, you should assume that it'll disappear while you're still alive.

931
00:48:37,930 --> 00:48:41,790
Scott: There's a trend lately of people doing things they want to disappear, like Snapchat and stuff.

932
00:48:41,830 --> 00:48:42,950
Rym: Yeah, ephemeral communication.

933
00:48:43,130 --> 00:48:49,808
Rym: Even though those things -- Actually, my only interest in those services is making clients that save everything anyway because fuck you.

934
00:48:50,450 --> 00:48:52,969
Scott: Right, well, people already can just take screenshots and do.

935
00:48:53,570 --> 00:48:56,630
Scott: It's not a big deal, but it's, you know, whatever.

936
00:48:57,170 --> 00:48:57,263
Scott: Yeah.

937
00:48:58,230 --> 00:49:02,449
Scott: It's great for the person -- It's really great for the company that runs it because they basically don't have to store it.

938
00:49:03,457 --> 00:49:07,885
Scott: They're basically like, "Hey, let's just run a shitty service where it's so cheap because we don't have to buy a million hard

939
00:49:07,905 --> 00:49:08,249
Scott: drives.".

940
00:49:08,372 --> 00:49:08,568
Scott: Brilliant.

941
00:49:09,050 --> 00:49:09,245
Scott: Brilliant.

942
00:49:09,972 --> 00:49:11,988
Scott: Super easy infrastructure compared to anyone else.

943
00:49:12,390 --> 00:49:20,129
Rym: So, if I had to guess things that are gonna die in the foreseeable near future, like years out, Google Voice is definitely gonna disappear.

944
00:49:20,390 --> 00:49:21,149
Scott: Well, that's for sure.

945
00:49:22,813 --> 00:49:25,030
Rym: I wonder what's gonna happen to Delicious in the long term.

946
00:49:25,472 --> 00:49:29,289
Rym: I don't -- Delicious, you know -- It costs so little to run is the only reason I think it'll hang on.

947
00:49:29,510 --> 00:49:31,549
Scott: And, like, people are working on it, and they bought it.

948
00:49:31,790 --> 00:49:33,946
Scott: It's like, but is it -- You know, it's a coin toss.

949
00:49:34,830 --> 00:49:36,770
Scott: I think it's got better odds than Google Voice, though.

950
00:49:36,971 --> 00:49:40,089
Rym: I think Pandora's gonna die, and I think Spotify's not gonna make it, either.

951
00:49:40,917 --> 00:49:41,389
Scott: I don't know.

952
00:49:41,610 --> 00:49:46,630
Scott: Those might be the kind of things where, like, Sirius XM Radio, it'll get merged, right?

953
00:49:46,651 --> 00:49:46,737
Rym: Yeah.

954
00:49:47,311 --> 00:49:48,309
Scott: I think that's what can happen.

955
00:49:48,830 --> 00:49:51,830
Scott: There'll be, like, one thing that takes -- Like, RDO, all three of those.

956
00:49:51,910 --> 00:49:52,409
Rym: Well, I'll say this.

957
00:49:52,571 --> 00:49:58,270
Rym: All your metadata in all those kinds of services will probably die unless you happen to pick the one that everyone merges into.

958
00:49:58,390 --> 00:50:00,270
Scott: That's why I don't put metadata into those services.

959
00:50:00,350 --> 00:50:10,950
Scott: I'm actually using Amazon Cloud Player, and that's a pretty good one because basically all it does is I'm actually using local iTunes, which is super safe, and then you basically mirror that to Amazon Cloud Player.

960
00:50:12,173 --> 00:50:13,530
Rym: I think Citi Bike's gonna die.

961
00:50:14,054 --> 00:50:14,850
Scott: That's not a cloud service.

962
00:50:15,050 --> 00:50:15,789
Rym: It's a physical service.

963
00:50:16,150 --> 00:50:16,240
Rym: Sure.

964
00:50:16,571 --> 00:50:17,409
Rym: I think it'll die, though.

965
00:50:19,258 --> 00:50:19,608
Scott: What else?

966
00:50:20,412 --> 00:50:20,750
Scott: I don't know.

967
00:50:20,830 --> 00:50:24,509
Scott: I mean, Flickr has probably better odds than Delicious, right, of being safe.

968
00:50:24,970 --> 00:50:27,289
Rym: Yeah, but at the same time, I don't trust Yahoo.

969
00:50:27,772 --> 00:50:27,923
Scott: No.

970
00:50:29,151 --> 00:50:38,527
Scott: But, yeah, anything that's, like, a tiny startup has really bad odds unless it's been -- And, you know, even if it gets bought by someone huge, it's like Beluga dead, right?

971
00:50:39,190 --> 00:50:44,050
Scott: It's like that GroupMe thing, that's as unstable as Beluga was, right, maybe a little bit more stable.

972
00:50:44,270 --> 00:50:52,850
Rym: And those two services are not likely to have competitor replacements because Google Hangouts and/or Facebook combined cover the use cases.

973
00:50:54,890 --> 00:50:57,930
Scott: You know, there's just -- what else is there?

974
00:50:58,650 --> 00:51:05,090
Scott: I guess Adobe Behance is gonna be -- I mean, Adobe's basically just gonna -- Behance is on this kind of upswing lately, which is interesting.

975
00:51:05,270 --> 00:51:12,110
Scott: Right, and Adobe Creative Cloud Storage, it's like, that's one of those things where I don't think too many people are using it compared to other things.

976
00:51:12,270 --> 00:51:13,649
Rym: I've never uploaded anything to it.

977
00:51:13,811 --> 00:51:17,730
Rym: Right, I've used it a tiny, tiny bit, but -- I should use it more, actually, 'cause it's free.

978
00:51:17,850 --> 00:51:19,390
Rym: I already pay for the Adobe stuff.

979
00:51:19,470 --> 00:51:31,290
Scott: Right, but, like, because it's something that people pay a zillion dollars for and Adobe just gives it to you for free, it's the kind of thing that will stick around likely, you know, probably even more likely than Flickr to stick around.

980
00:51:31,330 --> 00:51:36,850
Rym: Well, I think professional tools that cost significant money are a lot safer.

981
00:51:37,170 --> 00:51:41,050
Scott: Even if they don't have -- it's like, you don't need to have a lot of users to stick around, right?

982
00:51:41,550 --> 00:51:41,631
Rym: Yeah.

983
00:51:41,651 --> 00:51:45,450
Scott: Well, also, like, Adobe Creative Cloud -- 'Cause people are paying for it even if they're not using it.

984
00:51:45,530 --> 00:51:50,070
Rym: If all the things around that go down, that affects entire industries.

985
00:51:51,351 --> 00:51:53,909
Rym: Industries of professionals use that software in a daily basis.

